dataIdInfo.idAbs:
Calculates the base elevations and the maximum heights within Building footprint polygons. Two raster inputs are needed: a bare-earth Digital Terrain Model (DTM) is used to determine base elevation, and a normalized Digital Surface Model (nDSM) is used to determine maximum building height.

Once base elevation and height values are added to the footprint polygons, 3D buildings can be easily generated:

tool.name: CalculateBuildingElevations

param.name: inputBuildings
param.dialogReference: The Building footprint polygon feature class. If using the 3D Cities Information Model (3DCIM), check the box below.

param.name: idField
param.dialogReference: A unique field that can be used to identify the buildings - BuildingFID is recommended when using the 3D Cities Information Model (3DCIM). (The OBJECTID is not recommended as it will cause issues with some of the processes within the tool.)

param.name: input3DCIM
param.dialogReference:
Select this option if the input Building footprint feature class uses the 3D Cities Information Model (3DCIM) schema.

If checked, the totalHeightfield will be updated and the building footprint feature class will be Z-enabled. If unchecked, two new fields will be added to the input feature class: BaseHeight and BuildingHeight.

param.name: calcBaseHeight
param.dialogReference: Check this box to calculate the base elevation of each building footprint. In other words, the elevation where the base of the building will intersect with the terrain surface. Can be run in combination with the building height calcualtion, or by itself.

param.name: inputDEM
param.dialogReference: The input bare-earth Digital Terrain Model (DTM) raster. The elevation values contained within this raster will be used to Z-enable the Building polygons according to the selected Statistics Type.

param.name: statType
param.dialogReference:
Selects the statistic type that will be used by the base height (zonal statistics) tool to determine the Z value for each building. Mean is the default.

Selecting Minimum will situate buildings lower on the terrain (more of the building buried), while Maximum will situate them higher on the terrain (more of the building floating).

param.name: calcBuildingHeight
param.dialogReference:
Check this box to calculate maximum height of each building. Can be run in combination with the base elevation calculation, or by itself.

The maximum height value is written to the totalHeightattribute if using the 3DCIM schema, or to a new BuildingHeightfield if not.

param.name: inputNDSM
param.dialogReference:
The input normalized Digital Surface Model (nDSM) raster. The nDSM is calculated by subtracting the bare-earth terrain model from the surface model (DSM - DTM = nDSM), and represents a continous "height above ground" surface. These surfaces are easily calculated using classified LiDAR data.

The nDSM raster is used to calculate the maximum height value within each Building footprint, using zonal statistics.

param.name: useBuffer
param.dialogReference:
Check the box to enable a negative buffer on the building footprints before calculating the heights.

In some situations, a slight negative buffer should be used on the building polygons before calculating heights. This is often true of buildings which are adjacent to one another (e.g., row houses that share exterior walls) but have different heights. This will ensure that the height of a neighboring building does not influence the calculation.

param.name: BufferDist
param.dialogReference:
The negative buffer distance, in native units, used in the building height calculation. The default value is 2x the input nDSM raster resolution.

Note: applying a large negative buffer to a small building footprint (e.g., a garage) may cause no height value to be calculated.

tool.summary:
Calculates the base elevations and the maximum heights within Building footprint polygons. Two raster inputs are needed: a bare-earth Digital Terrain Model (DTM) is used to determine base elevation, and a normalized Digital Surface Model (nDSM) is used to determine maximum building height.

Once base elevation and height values are added to the footprint polygons, 3D buildings can be easily generated:
tool.usage: Populates the totalHeightattribute in the Building feature class with the heights obtained from the normalized Digital Surface Model (nDSM). The Building features are then z-enabled according to the base elevation. Each calculation can be done independently or at the same time.
